      "teaser": "Just by looking at something, you change it. Seriously.",
      "fact": "This is the Observer Effect, and it's arguably the most mind-bending result in the history of science. In the famous Double Slit Experiment, scientists fire particles (like electrons or photons) at a barrier with two slits. When nobody's watching, the particles create an interference pattern on the back wall — a wavy pattern that proves they're traveling as WAVES and going through BOTH slits simultaneously.\n\nBut here's where it gets absolutely wild. When scientists add a detector to watch which slit each particle goes through, the interference pattern vanishes. The particles suddenly start acting like little marbles, going through one slit or the other — never both. The simple act of observing them forces them to \"choose\" a definite path. It's as if the particles know they're being watched.\n\nNow, \"observing\" doesn't mean a conscious human has to be staring at it. Any interaction that extracts information — a detector, a photon bouncing off the particle, any measurement at all — collapses the particle's wave function. It goes from being a spread-out wave of possibilities to a single, specific outcome. The information itself is what matters.\n\nThis experiment has been repeated thousands of times with electrons, photons, atoms, even molecules, and the result is always the same. Reality, at its most fundamental level, doesn't seem to exist in a definite state until it's measured. Let that land for a second: the universe doesn't decide what's real until something asks. That's not science fiction — that's physics.",
