      "teaser": "Why your GPS will never be perfectly accurate — and it's not a tech problem",
      "fact": "Heisenberg's Uncertainty Principle is one of the fundamental laws of quantum mechanics, and it says something genuinely shocking: you CANNOT perfectly know a particle's exact position and its exact momentum (speed and direction) at the same time. The more precisely you pin down where something is, the less you can know about how fast it's moving, and vice versa. This isn't a limitation of our instruments — it's a fundamental property of nature itself.\n\nThink of it this way: to \"see\" where a tiny particle is, you need to bounce something off it — like a photon of light. But photons carry energy, and when they hit the particle, they give it a little kick, changing its momentum. Use a higher-energy photon for a sharper image, and you kick it harder. You can get a perfect snapshot of position, but now you've completely scrambled the momentum. There's no way around it.\n\nThis principle echoes all the way up into everyday technology. Your GPS works by timing signals from satellites with incredible precision, but there are fundamental quantum limits to how precisely those atomic clocks can be synchronized. Engineering gets you to within a few feet, but the last tiny fractions of precision are eaten up by the uncertainty principle itself. The universe has a built-in blur.\n\nAnd here's the deep philosophical punch: the uncertainty principle means the universe is fundamentally fuzzy at the bottom. There's no such thing as a particle with a perfectly defined position AND a perfectly defined speed. Reality, at its most fundamental level, isn't made of certainties — it's made of probabilities. Heisenberg didn't discover a limit to what we can know. He discovered a limit to what there IS to know.",
