      "teaser": "Somewhere, another version of you didn't open this app",
      "fact": "The Many-Worlds Interpretation, proposed by physicist Hugh Everett in 1957, is one of the most audacious ideas in the history of science. It says that every time a quantum event has multiple possible outcomes, the universe doesn't pick one — it splits into EVERY possible outcome, each playing out in its own parallel branch of reality. Every quantum decision creates new universes.\n\nSo right now, in some branch of the multiverse, you didn't open this app. In another, you're reading a completely different fact. In another, you decided to have pizza instead of whatever you had for dinner. And in yet another branch, dinosaurs never went extinct, and clever velociraptors are reading THEIR version of this app. (Okay, that last one might be a stretch, but the point stands.)\n\nThe wild thing is, this interpretation actually solves one of the biggest puzzles in quantum mechanics: the measurement problem. Instead of a wave function \"collapsing\" into one outcome (which nobody can explain the mechanism for), ALL outcomes happen — you just find yourself in one particular branch. There's no collapse, no mystery, no special role for \"observation.\" The math is cleaner and simpler than the standard interpretation.\n\nOf course, we can't communicate with or detect these other branches — they're completely separate from our experience once they split. Critics call it untestable and therefore unscientific. Supporters call it the simplest interpretation of the math. Either way, it's taken seriously by a significant chunk of physicists and cosmologists, and it raises the most profound philosophical question in science: if infinite versions of you exist, what does \"you\" even mean?",
