      "teaser": "Sunlight is physically pushing you right now — and we've built sails for it",
      "fact": "Light has momentum. Actual, physical, push-you-around momentum. Even though photons have zero mass, they carry momentum proportional to their energy (thanks to Einstein's E=pc). When sunlight hits your skin, it's exerting a real, measurable force on you — roughly the weight of a single grain of sand spread across your entire body. Tiny, but absolutely real.\n\nScientists and engineers have turned this into a propulsion system. Solar sails are spacecraft that use enormous, ultra-thin reflective sheets to catch the push of sunlight — exactly like wind sails catch the breeze, but in the vacuum of space. And because sunlight is always shining, solar sails can accelerate continuously for months and years, eventually reaching speeds that traditional rocket fuel can't match.\n\nThis isn't science fiction. Japan's IKAROS spacecraft successfully demonstrated solar sail technology in 2010, navigating through space using nothing but the pressure of sunlight. The Planetary Society's LightSail 2 orbited Earth using only solar pressure, and the NEA Scout mission used a solar sail to visit an asteroid. We're literally sailing through space on beams of light.\n\nThe Breakthrough Starshot initiative takes this to the extreme: a proposed mission to Alpha Centauri (our nearest star system, 4.37 light-years away) using tiny spacecraft propelled by a massive Earth-based laser array. The plan is to accelerate gram-scale probes to 20% the speed of light, reaching Alpha Centauri in about 20 years. If it works, humanity's first interstellar mission will be powered by nothing more exotic than light pushing on a mirror. Sometimes the most elegant solutions are also the simplest.",
