      "teaser": "You look through windows every day, but the reason they're clear is mind-bending",
      "fact": "You'd think something as simple as \"windows are transparent\" would have a simple explanation. It doesn't. The reason glass is see-through is a beautiful piece of quantum mechanics that has to do with how electrons absorb (or refuse to absorb) photons of light.\n\nIn any material, electrons exist in energy bands — think of them as allowed \"floors\" in a building. To absorb a photon, an electron has to jump from a lower floor to a higher floor. But here's the catch: it can ONLY absorb a photon if the photon's energy EXACTLY matches the gap between floors. No partial absorptions allowed. In glass, the gap between the electron bands is so large that visible light photons don't have enough energy to make any electron jump. So the photons pass right through, completely ignored.\n\nThis is why glass is transparent to visible light but opaque to ultraviolet! UV photons have higher energy, enough to bridge that gap and get absorbed. It's also why your sunglasses can block UV while letting you see through them — different photon energies interact with the material differently.\n\nEvery time you look through a window, you're witnessing quantum mechanics in action. The photons carrying the image of the tree outside are streaming through the glass because not a single electron in that glass has the right energy gap to absorb them. Billions of photons, all politely passing through because the quantum math doesn't work out for absorption. The universe runs on VERY strict accounting, and that accounting is why you can see outside right now.",
