      "teaser": "Electrons spin — but not the way anything you've ever seen spins",
      "fact": "Quantum spin is one of those concepts that physicists named poorly and then had to spend the next century explaining. When physicists say an electron \"spins,\" they do NOT mean it's rotating like a basketball on your finger. Quantum spin is something with no everyday analogy — it's a fundamental, intrinsic property of a particle, like mass or charge, that happens to behave mathematically like angular momentum.\n\nHere's how weird it gets: an electron has spin-½, which means it has to rotate 720 degrees — TWO full rotations — to get back to its original state. Imagine spinning around in your desk chair. You'd expect that after one full turn (360°), everything looks the same. But for an electron, after one full rotation, it's actually in a NEGATIVE version of its original state. It takes two full rotations to truly return to the start. Nothing in everyday experience works like this.\n\nSpin has enormous consequences. It determines how particles organize themselves, which gives us the Pauli Exclusion Principle — no two electrons in an atom can have the same quantum state. This single rule is why the periodic table exists, why chemistry works, why atoms form bonds, and why matter has any structure at all. Without spin, electrons would all collapse into the lowest energy level, atoms would be featureless blobs, and complex matter (including you) couldn't exist.\n\nAnd it gets even cooler: spin is what makes MRI machines work. When you lie in an MRI scanner, a powerful magnetic field aligns the spin of hydrogen atoms in your body. Radio waves then flip those spins, and when they snap back, they emit signals that the machine reads to create images of your insides. You're literally getting a medical scan thanks to a property that doesn't correspond to anything actually spinning. Quantum mechanics is weird, but it saves lives.",
