    {
      "teaser": "What if your next birthday already exists right now, somewhere in spacetime?",
      "fact": "Welcome to the block universe — one of the most mind-bending consequences of Einstein's relativity. In this framework, the past, present, and future all exist simultaneously. Your birthday next year isn't something that \"will happen\" — it already exists, right now, as a real location in the four-dimensional fabric of spacetime. You just haven't traveled to that point in the time dimension yet.\n\nThis comes directly from Einstein's Special Relativity and the fact that there's no universal \"now.\" If you and someone flying past Earth at 80% the speed of light both try to define what's happening \"right now\" on a distant planet, you'll disagree — and both of you are equally correct. There's no absolute present moment. This means the future that one observer experiences as \"now\" is someone else's \"not yet,\" which implies both the past and future must be just as real as the present.\n\nPhysicists call this the \"block universe\" or \"eternalism\" — the idea that all of spacetime exists as one giant, unchanging four-dimensional block. Time doesn't \"flow\" — it just IS. Our perception of past, present, and future is like a spotlight moving along a filmstrip that already contains every frame. The movie doesn't change; our awareness of it does.\n\nBut here's the quantum wrinkle: while relativity gives us the block universe, quantum mechanics introduces genuine randomness and uncertainty. The future might \"exist\" in some sense, but it might exist as a superposition of MANY possible futures until quantum events collapse into specific outcomes. So maybe all your possible birthdays exist out there in spacetime — the version where you get the gift you wanted AND the version where you don't. The universe might be less like a single filmstrip and more like an infinite branching choose-your-own-adventure book.",
    },
    {
      "teaser": "The universe has a speed limit that even the weirdest physics can't break",
      "fact": "Entanglement looks like it breaks the cosmic speed limit. Two entangled particles, separated by any distance, seem to influence each other instantly — faster than light. Einstein called it \"spooky action at a distance\" and spent decades trying to disprove it. But here's the catch that saves physics: you can't actually USE entanglement to send a message faster than light.\n\nHere's why: when you measure your entangled particle and instantly know what the distant particle's measurement will be, that knowledge is useless for communication. Your measurement result appears random to you — heads or tails, spin-up or spin-down — and there's no way to control what you get. Your partner sees their correlated result, also appearing random to them. It's only when you COMPARE notes (which has to happen through a normal, speed-of-light-limited channel) that the spooky correlations become apparent.\n\nThis is called the \"no-communication theorem,\" and it's a proven mathematical fact of quantum mechanics. No matter how clever your setup, entanglement cannot transmit usable information faster than light. Causality — the principle that causes must precede their effects — is preserved. The universe's speed limit stands unbroken.\n\nSo what IS entanglement doing if it's not sending information? That's one of the deepest open questions in physics. It's creating correlations that are stronger than anything possible in classical physics, but it's doing so without any signal traveling between the particles. It's as if the two particles are secretly the same object, just wearing different costumes in different locations. Some physicists think entanglement reveals something profound about the structure of spacetime itself — and understanding it fully might be the key to quantum gravity.",
    },
    {
      "teaser": "The strongest force in the universe is inside every atom in your body",
      "fact": "The strong nuclear force is roughly 100 times stronger than electromagnetism, 10,000 times stronger than the weak nuclear force, and a mind-melting 10³⁸ times stronger than gravity. Without it, atomic nuclei couldn't exist, because the positively charged protons inside would fly apart from electromagnetic repulsion. The strong force is the cosmic glue holding every atom in the universe together.\n\nBut here's the wildest part: the strong force has a property called \"confinement\" that makes it behave like nothing else in physics. Try to pull two quarks apart, and the force between them doesn't get weaker with distance — it gets STRONGER, like stretching a rubber band. Pull hard enough, and instead of separating the quarks, the energy you've put in creates entirely new quarks from the vacuum. You literally cannot isolate a single quark. Nobody has ever seen one alone, and the theory says no one ever will.\n\nQuarks (the particles inside protons and neutrons) are held together by force-carrying particles called gluons — and here's another unique twist: gluons themselves carry the charge that creates the strong force (called \"color charge\"). This would be like if photons (which carry the electromagnetic force) were themselves electrically charged. It makes the strong force incredibly complicated and nonlinear, which is why it took decades of genius-level physics to even partially understand.\n\nThe strong force is also why nuclear energy is so absurdly powerful. When heavy atoms split (fission) or light atoms combine (fusion), they're rearranging the strong force bonds between nucleons, releasing a tiny fraction of that enormous binding energy. A single nuclear reaction releases about a million times more energy than a chemical reaction. The Sun, every nuclear reactor, and every nuclear weapon runs on the strong force. The strongest force in the universe has been powering your world all along.",
    },
    {
      "teaser": "Remove all the empty space in humanity and 8 billion people fit in a sugar cube",
      "fact": "This is absolutely, terrifyingly true. If you could remove all the empty space inside every atom in every human being on Earth, the remaining matter — just the actual protons, neutrons, and electrons, packed tightly together — would fit in a volume roughly the size of a sugar cube. All 8 billion of us. Into something you could balance on a spoon.\n\nTo understand why, remember the incredible emptiness inside atoms. If the nucleus of an atom were a marble on the 50-yard line of a football stadium, the closest electrons would be gnats buzzing around in the nosebleed seats. Everything in between? Absolutely nothing. And the nucleus itself is tiny — about 100,000 times smaller than the atom. The vast, VAST majority of what makes up \"you\" is forces and emptiness.\n\nThis is actually what happens inside neutron stars — the collapsed cores of dead massive stars. When gravity crushes atoms so hard that the electrons are squeezed into the protons (forming neutrons), all that empty space gets removed. The result is matter so dense that a teaspoon weighs about 6 billion tons. A sugar cube of neutron star material on Earth would weigh roughly as much as Mount Everest.\n\nSo why don't we collapse like neutron stars? Because the electromagnetic force between the electron clouds of neighboring atoms is powerful enough to resist compression at the scales and pressures we experience. Your body is a delicate balance of forces maintaining a structure that's 99.9999999% nothing. You're a scaffolding of forces keeping empty space in place. Billions of years of cosmic engineering went into making you successfully pretend to be solid.",
    },
    {
      "teaser": "Even at the coldest temperature imaginable, nothing ever truly stops moving",
      "fact": "Absolute zero — 0 Kelvin, or −273.15°C — is the coldest anything can theoretically get. It's the point where classical physics says all molecular motion should stop dead. But quantum mechanics threw a wrench in that plan. Even at absolute zero, particles retain what's called zero-point energy — a small but non-zero minimum energy that can never be removed.\n\nWhy? The Uncertainty Principle strikes again. If a particle could be perfectly still, you'd know both its exact position (wherever it stopped) and its exact momentum (zero). But Heisenberg says you can't know both perfectly. So particles at absolute zero must keep jittering — a tiny, irreducible quantum shiver — to maintain the necessary uncertainty.\n\nThis has been experimentally verified with superfluid helium. Liquid helium-4, when cooled to near absolute zero, becomes a superfluid — a liquid with zero viscosity that can climb up walls, flow through molecule-thin cracks, and drip through solid containers. This bizarre behavior is a direct consequence of zero-point energy and quantum mechanical effects dominating the helium atoms' behavior. Even at the bottom of the temperature scale, quantum weirdness takes over.\n\nZero-point energy also shows up across all of physics. It's responsible for the Casimir effect, it contributes to vacuum energy, and some (controversial) scientists have proposed that it could theoretically be harnessed as an energy source. We haven't figured out how to do that — and many physicists think it's impossible — but the energy is undeniably there. The universe has a minimum vibration speed, and it's greater than zero. Absolute stillness is not just hard to achieve — it's prohibited by the laws of physics.",
    },
    {
      "teaser": "Black holes aren't forever — they're slowly evaporating",
      "fact": "Stephen Hawking dropped this bombshell in 1974 and it shook the foundations of physics. Black holes — objects so massive that nothing, not even light, can escape their gravitational pull — are slowly, gradually leaking energy and shrinking. Given enough time (we're talking unimaginably long timescales), they'll evaporate completely. Hawking radiation is the mechanism, and it's a stunning intersection of quantum mechanics and gravity.\n\nHere's how it works: near the event horizon, those quantum fluctuations we talked about — virtual particle-antiparticle pairs constantly popping into existence — get torn apart by the black hole's intense gravity. One particle falls in, and the other escapes. The escaping particle carries away a tiny bit of energy, and since energy equals mass (thanks, Einstein), the black hole gets a little bit lighter with each escaped particle. Over time, it slowly shrinks.\n\nHawking radiation means black holes have a temperature — and smaller black holes are actually HOTTER than bigger ones. A black hole with the mass of our Sun would have a temperature barely above absolute zero (trillionths of a degree), taking roughly 10⁶⁷ years to evaporate. But a tiny black hole the mass of a mountain would glow white-hot and explode in a final burst of radiation in a relatively short time.\n\nThe deepest consequence of Hawking radiation is the black hole information paradox: when a black hole evaporates, what happens to all the information about everything that fell in? Quantum mechanics says information can never be destroyed, but the black hole is gone. This paradox has sparked decades of debate, leading to ideas like the holographic principle, black hole firewalls, and ER=EPR (a proposed connection between wormholes and entanglement). A good chunk of modern theoretical physics is basically an argument about what happens when black holes die.",
    },
    {
      "teaser": "85% of the universe is made of something no one has ever seen or touched",
      "fact": "Dark matter is one of the greatest mysteries in the universe — a substance that makes up about 27% of all mass-energy in the cosmos, doesn't interact with light at all (making it completely invisible), and has never been directly detected. We know it's there because of its gravity — galaxies don't have nearly enough visible matter to hold together at the speeds they spin. Something unseen is providing the extra gravitational glue.\n\nThe evidence is overwhelming and comes from multiple independent observations. Galaxy rotation curves are flat when they should be declining (first observed by Vera Rubin in the 1970s). Galaxy clusters bend light from behind them (gravitational lensing) far more than their visible mass accounts for. The cosmic microwave background radiation — the afterglow of the Big Bang — has patterns that only make sense if dark matter was there in the early universe, seeding the formation of galaxies.\n\nSo what IS it? Nobody knows. The leading candidates are hypothetical particles called WIMPs (Weakly Interacting Massive Particles), axions (extremely light particles predicted by other theories), or primordial black holes. Scientists have built detectors deep underground, in abandoned mines and beneath mountains, trying to catch dark matter particles interacting with normal matter. So far — nothing. Billions of dark matter particles probably passed through your body in the time it took to read this sentence, and not a single one interacted with you.\n\nHere's the humbling punchline: all the stars, planets, gas, dust, and everything you've ever seen, touched, or measured — all of chemistry, biology, and everyday physics — makes up only about 5% of the total stuff in the universe. The remaining 95% is dark matter (27%) and dark energy (68%), and we don't really understand either one. The universe isn't just stranger than we suppose — it's stranger than we CAN suppose, and most of it is invisible.",
    },
    {
      "teaser": "Electrons don't orbit like planets — and that's why your phone screen glows",
      "fact": "Forget every diagram you've ever seen of electrons circling a nucleus like tiny planets. That model (the Bohr model) is a useful simplification, but it's fundamentally wrong. In reality, electrons exist in clouds of probability called orbitals — three-dimensional shapes that describe WHERE the electron is likely to be found, but never where it definitely IS, until you measure it.\n\nThese orbitals have bizarre shapes: spheres (s-orbitals), dumbbells (p-orbitals), cloverleaves (d-orbitals), and even weirder shapes for f-orbitals. The electron doesn't follow a path through space — it's smeared out across the entire orbital simultaneously, like a fuzzy cloud of probability. It's not that we don't know where it is. The electron genuinely doesn't have a definite location until something measures it.\n\nThis has enormous practical consequences. When electrons jump between orbitals (from a high-energy orbital to a low-energy one), they release the energy difference as a photon — a specific frequency of light. THAT is how your phone screen glows. LED screens work by engineering the orbital energy gaps in semiconductor materials so that electrons jumping down produce photons of exactly the right color — red, green, or blue. Every pixel on your screen is electrons dropping between probability clouds and spitting out precisely tuned photons.\n\nThe planetary model of atoms is one of the most persistent wrong ideas in science education, and it's a shame, because the real picture is so much cooler. Atoms aren't tiny solar systems — they're quantum clouds of probability where particles don't have definite positions, and their transitions between states produce the light that lets you read this sentence. You're staring at quantum mechanics right now. You always have been.",
    },
    {
      "teaser": "The reason red looks red has nothing to do with the color itself",
      "fact": "In particle physics, quarks — the fundamental building blocks inside protons and neutrons — have a property called \"color charge.\" It comes in three types: red, green, and blue. But here's the thing — this has ABSOLUTELY nothing to do with actual colors. Like, zero. Zilch. Physicists chose the names because the math works out similarly to how red, green, and blue light combine to make white light. Quarks with all three color charges together make a \"colorless\" (stable) particle.\n\nThe strong nuclear force, which holds quarks together, operates through this color charge system. Gluons — the force-carrying particles of the strong force — also carry color charge, which is wildly unusual. It's like if the electromagnetic force's photons were themselves electrically charged. This makes the math of the strong force (called Quantum Chromodynamics, or QCD) incredibly complex and nonlinear.\n\nHere's a fun rule: only \"colorless\" combinations of quarks can exist freely in nature. You can combine a red, green, and blue quark to make a baryon (like a proton or neutron), or a quark and antiquark of complementary colors to make a meson. But you'll never find a naked quark or a pair of quarks with the same color — the force literally won't allow it. This is called color confinement, and if you try to pull quarks apart, the energy creates new quarks to maintain colorlessness. Nature follows its own RGB palette rules.\n\nSo the next time someone says \"red,\" remember there are TWO completely unrelated things that word can mean. There's the red your eyes see — photons with wavelengths around 620–750 nanometers hitting your retina. And then there's \"red\" as a quantum property of quarks that describes how the strong force works inside every atom in your body. One you can see. The other will never be visible to any instrument, ever, no matter how advanced. Physics loves recycling vocabulary just to keep things confusing.",
    },
  ];

  // Bump this whenever TaskType enum changes so stale caches are discarded.
  static const int _feedVersion = 4;

  static Future<List<QuantumPost>> generateDailyFeed() async {
    final prefs = await SharedPreferences.getInstance();
    
    // Check if we have a saved feed for today AND same version
    final now = DateTime.now();
    final todayStr = "${now.year}-${now.month}-${now.day}";
    final savedDate = prefs.getString('daily_feed_date');
    final savedVersion = prefs.getInt('daily_feed_version') ?? 0;
    final savedFeedJson = prefs.getString('daily_feed_data');

    if (savedDate == todayStr && savedVersion == _feedVersion && savedFeedJson != null) {
      try {
        final List<dynamic> decoded = jsonDecode(savedFeedJson);
        return decoded.map((item) => QuantumPost.fromJson(item as Map<String, dynamic>)).toList();
      } catch (e) {
        // Fallback to regenerate
      }
    }

    // We shuffle the facts to pick 25 unique ones
    final shuffledFacts = List<Map<String, String>>.from(_factPool)..shuffle(_rand);
    
    // Select 25
    final selectedFacts = shuffledFacts.take(25).toList();

    final newFeed = List.generate(25, (index) {
      final factData = selectedFacts[index];
      final taskType = TaskType.values[_rand.nextInt(TaskType.values.length)];
      
      return QuantumPost(
        id: "post_$index\u0024{_rand.nextInt(10000)}", // Made ID slightly more unique for the seed
        teaserText: factData['teaser']!,
        fullFactText: factData['fact']!,
        taskType: taskType,
      );
    });

    // Save to SharedPreferences
    final jsonList = newFeed.map((post) => post.toJson()).toList();
    await prefs.setString('daily_feed_date', todayStr);
    await prefs.setInt('daily_feed_version', _feedVersion);
    await prefs.setString('daily_feed_data', jsonEncode(jsonList));

    return newFeed;
  }
}
